review_blob: Pours thin, dark amber in appearance.  Very little head, though it does attempt to lace somewhat.  The aroma hints of vanilla, and through the forward carbonation, I can taste a chocolate malt with a vanilla finish.  Overall it isnt bad, but its lack of body does not impress.  A pretty average porter.

Snifter at Triumph Brew Co in Philly.  Poured a much thinner brew than expected.  However, mildly chocolate with significant coffee aroma.  Somewhat thin mouthfeel, but very satisfying and surprisingly complex.  Finishes clean, with possibly minimal amounts of vanilla.

Served at a Philly Irish Pub in a pint glass.  If no one had told me the ABV, I wouldnt have noticed.  Poured a lovely golden pint, exceptionally clear.  Mouthfeel was smooth with a subtle lingering of hops.  Would recommend.

Bottle served in a snifter.  Not a whole lot of head despite serious attempts.  However, this pours dark and rich, with a chocolate/nutty aroma.  The bottle says "chewy" and this is evident on the first taste, in such a good way.  Mouthfeel is thick and smooth, Oso wonderful.  Despite being a porter, this is reminiscent of Founders KBS.  There is little hint of the ABV however, and this can sneak up on you while enjoying.  Makes Wisconsin proud.

12 oz bottle, served just below room temp.  Pour is noticeably viscous, rich and dark.  Leaves a tan brown head that lingers just long enough.  Aroma is sweet chocolate with hints of bourbon.  Hits the palate with a velvety richness speaking mocha, chocolate and aftertaste of the bourbon and vanilla.  Cannot say enough about the mouthfeel,so so smooth.  An absolutely great beer meant to drink slow.
